  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Patients with scarring of the liver (cirrhosis) and portal hypertension (elevated blood
      pressure in the liver vasculature) can develop esophageal varices (dilated veins). These have
      an increased risk of bleeding each year. Current recommendations are to prevent bleeding of
      medium or large varices (when there is no history of bleeding) by starting a blood pressure
      lowering agent known as a non-selective beta-blocker. Alternatively, rubber bands can be
      placed on medium to large varices to prevent bleeding (endoscopic variceal band ligation).
      Using both therapies at the same time has not been studied. In this study, we hope to
      determine if the use of combination therapy with endoscopic variceal band ligation and beta
      blockers is more effective than using beta blockers alone to prevent the first bleeding
      episode from the varices (dilated veins). The efficacy, ability to tolerate, and
      cost-effectiveness of these two treatment strategies will be compared.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
